                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.5914/127</note>
                            <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Copenhagen</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-08-26T13:00:00+02:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 26, 1916, 1 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>331. Your 155, August 24th, 3 p.m. Owing to the widely current rumor
                                here that the United States is putting undue pressure on Denmark for
                                the cession within a time limit of the islands, I have been obliged
                                to say authoritatively that there is no such pressure. I referred to
                                the words of the published treaty and said that the only pressure
                                was the expressed wish that the matter might be expedited as soon as
                                possible. Paris <hi rend="italic">New York Herald</hi> of August
                                20th in an interview with a distinguished Dane echoes these
                                rumors.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Egan</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
